<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For the retr=
onym referring to television broadcasting, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Broadcast_programming" title=3D"Broadcast programming">Broadca=
st programming</a>.</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Linear_optimization_in_a_2-dimensional_polyto=
pe.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.=
org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Linear_optimization_in_a_2-dimensional_pol=
ytope.svg/250px-Linear_optimization_in_a_2-dimensional_polytope.svg.png" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"243" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"557" data-file-height=3D"542"></a><figcaption>A pictorial r=
epresentation of a simple linear program with two variables and six inequal=
ities. The set of feasible solutions is depicted in yellow and forms a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon" title=3D"Polygon">polygon</a>=
, a 2-dimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polytope" title=
=3D"Polytope">polytope</a>. The optimum of the linear cost function is wher=
e the red line intersects the polygon. The red line is a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Level_set" title=3D"Level set">level set</a> of the =
cost function, and the arrow indicates the direction in which we are optimi=
zing.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:3dpoly.svg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thu=
mb/e/ef/3dpoly.svg/250px-3dpoly.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" h=
eight=3D"233" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"647" data-file-h=
eight=3D"602"></a><figcaption>A closed feasible region of a problem with th=
ree variables is a convex <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedr=
on" title=3D"Polyhedron">polyhedron</a>. The surfaces giving a fixed value =
of the objective function are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plan=
e_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plane (geometry)">planes</a> (=
not shown). The linear programming problem is to find a point on the polyhe=
dron that is on the plane with the highest possible value.</figcaption></fi=
gure>
<p><b>Linear programming</b> (<b>LP</b>), also called <b>linear optimizatio=
n</b>, is a method to achieve the best outcome (such as maximum profit or l=
owest cost) in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_mode=
l" title=3D"Mathematical model">mathematical model</a> whose requirements a=
nd objective are represented by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li=
near_function#As_a_polynomial_function" title=3D"Linear function">linear re=
lationships</a>. Linear programming is a special case of mathematical progr=
amming (also known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical=
_optimization" title=3D"Mathematical optimization">mathematical optimizatio=
n</a>).
</p><p>More formally, linear programming is a technique for the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_optimization" title=3D"Mathemati=
cal optimization">optimization</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Linear" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear">linear</a> <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Objective_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Objective function">objective function</a>, subject to <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_equality" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Linear equality">linear equality</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Linear_inequality" title=3D"Linear inequality">linear inequality</a>=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constraint_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Constraint (mathematics)">constraints</a>. Its <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Feasible_region" title=3D"Feasible region">feasible region=
</a> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polytope" title=
=3D"Convex polytope">convex polytope</a>, which is a set defined as the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intersection_(mathematics)" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Intersection (mathematics)">intersection</a> of finit=
ely many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-space_(geometry)" ti=
tle=3D"Half-space (geometry)">half spaces</a>, each of which is defined by =
a linear inequality. Its objective function is a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real</a>-valued <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affine_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Affine function">affine (linear) function</a> defined on this polyto=
pe. A linear programming <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm=
" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a> finds a point in the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polytope" title=3D"Polytope">polytope</a> where this=
 function has the largest (or smallest) value if such a point exists.
</p><p>Linear programs are problems that can be expressed in <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canonical_form" title=3D"Canonical form">standar=
d form</a> as:
</p>
