 over which the objective function is to be optimized.
</p><p>Linear programming can be applied to various fields of study. It is =
widely used in mathematics and, to a lesser extent, in business, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Economics">economics</a>=
, and some engineering problems. There is a close connection between linear=
 programs, eigenequations, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_vo=
n_Neumann" title=3D"John von Neumann">John von Neumann</a>'s general equili=
brium model, and structural equilibrium models (see <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_linear_program" title=3D"Dual linear program">dual l=
inear program</a> for details).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-1"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Industries that use linear programming models include transportation, energ=
y, telecommunications, and manufacturing. It has proven useful in modeling =
diverse types of problems in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autom=
ated_planning_and_scheduling" title=3D"Automated planning and scheduling">p=
lanning</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Routing" title=3D"Rou=
ting">routing</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scheduling_(pro=
duction_processes)" title=3D"Scheduling (production processes)">scheduling<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assignment_problem" title=3D"=
Assignment problem">assignment</a>, and design.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_programming&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leonid_Kantorovich_1975.jpg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/f/f4/Leonid_Kantorovich_1975.jpg/250px-Leonid_Kantorovich_1975.jpg" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"322" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"520" data-file-height=3D"670"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonid_Kantorovich" title=3D"Leonid Kantorovich"=
>Leonid Kantorovich</a></figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:JohnvonNeumann-LosAlamos.gif" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t=
humb/5/5e/JohnvonNeumann-LosAlamos.gif/250px-JohnvonNeumann-LosAlamos.gif" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"326" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"490" data-file-height=3D"639"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_von_Neumann" title=3D"John von Neumann">=
John von Neumann</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>The problem of solving a system of linear inequalities dates back at lea=
st as far as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Fourier" title=
=3D"Joseph Fourier">Fourier</a>, who in 1827 published a method for solving=
 them,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SierksmaZwols2015_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-SierksmaZwo=
ls2015-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> and after whom the method of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Fourier%E2%80%93Motzkin_elimination" title=3D"Fourier=E2=80=
=93Motzkin elimination">Fourier=E2=80=93Motzkin elimination</a> is named.
</p><p>In the late 1930s, Soviet mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Leonid_Kantorovich" title=3D"Leonid Kantorovich">Leonid Kantor=
ovich</a> and American economist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W=
assily_Leontief" title=3D"Wassily Leontief">Wassily Leontief</a> independen=
tly delved into the practical applications of linear programming. Kantorovi=
ch focused on manufacturing schedules, while Leontief explored economic app=
lications. Their groundbreaking work was largely overlooked for decades.
</p><p>The turning point came during World War II when linear programming e=
merged as a vital tool. It found extensive use in addressing complex wartim=
e challenges, including transportation logistics, scheduling, and resource =
allocation. Linear programming proved invaluable in optimizing these proces=
ses while considering critical constraints such as costs and resource avail=
ability.
</p><p>Despite its initial obscurity, the wartime successes propelled linea=
r programming into the spotlight. Post-WWII, the method gained widespread r=
ecognition and became a cornerstone in various fields, from operations rese=
arch to economics. The overlooked contributions of Kantorovich and Leontief=
 in the late 1930s eventually became foundational to the broader acceptance=
 and utilization of linear programming in optimizing decision-making proces=
ses.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Kantorovich's work was initially neglected in the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USSR" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"USSR">USSR</a>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dantzig1982_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-dantzig1982-6"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> About the same time as Kantorovich, the Dutch-American economist <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tjalling_Koopmans" title=3D"Tjalling Koop=
mans">T. C. Koopmans</a> formulated classical economic problems as linear p=
rograms. Kantorovich and Koopmans later shared the 1975 <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Memorial_Prize_in_Economic_Sciences" title=3D"N=
obel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences">Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic =
Sciences</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SierksmaZwols2015_4-1" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-Sier=
ksmaZwols2015-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1941, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Frank_Lauren_Hitchcock" title=3D"Frank Lauren Hitchcock">Frank Lauren Hi=
tchcock</a> also formulated transportation problems as linear programs and =
gave a solution very similar to the later <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Simplex_method" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Simplex method">simp=
lex method</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Schrijver1998_7-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-Schrij=
ver1998-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> Hitchcock had died in 1957, and the Nobel Memorial Pr=
ize is not awarded posthumously.
</p><p>From 1946 to 1947 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Da=
ntzig" title=3D"George Dantzig">George B. Dantzig</a> independently develop=
ed general linear programming formulation to use for planning problems in t=
he US Air Force.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-:0-8"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 In 1947, Dantzig also invented the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Simplex_algorithm" title=3D"Simplex algorithm">simplex method</a> that, f=
or the first time efficiently, tackled the linear programming problem in mo=
st cases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_8-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-:0-8"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> When D=
antzig arranged a meeting with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joh=
n_von_Neumann" title=3D"John von Neumann">John von Neumann</a> to discuss h=
is simplex method, von Neumann immediately conjectured the theory of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#Duality">duality</a> =
by realizing that the problem he had been working in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory" title=3D"Game theory">game theory</a> was e=
quivalent.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_8-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-:0-8"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Dantz=
ig provided formal proof in an unpublished report "A Theorem on Linear Ineq=
ualities" on January 5, 1948.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dantzig1982_6-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite=
_note-dantzig1982-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Dantzig's work was made available to public=
 in 1951. In the post-war years, many industries applied it in their daily =
planning.
</p><p>Dantzig's original example was to find the best assignment of 70 peo=
ple to 70 jobs. The computing power required to test all the permutations t=
o select the best assignment is vast; the number of possible configurations=
 exceeds the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abundance_of_the_chem=
ical_elements" title=3D"Abundance of the chemical elements">number of parti=
cles</a> in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observable_univers=
e" title=3D"Observable universe">observable universe</a>. However, it takes=
 only a moment to find the optimum solution by posing the problem as a line=
ar program and applying the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple=
x_algorithm" title=3D"Simplex algorithm">simplex algorithm</a>. The theory =
behind linear programming drastically reduces the number of possible soluti=
ons that must be checked.
</p><p>The linear programming problem was first shown to be solvable in pol=
ynomial time by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonid_Khachiyan" =
title=3D"Leonid Khachiyan">Leonid Khachiyan</a> in 1979,<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-khachiyan79_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Linear_programming#cite_note-khachiyan79-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but a larger the=
oretical and practical breakthrough in the field came in 1984 when <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narendra_Karmarkar" title=3D"Narendra Kar=
markar">Narendra Karmarkar</a> introduced a new <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Interior-point_method" title=3D"Interior-point method">interi=
or-point method</a> for solving linear-programming problems.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-karmarkar84_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-karmarkar84-10"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Uses">Uses</h2><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_programming&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Uses"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Linear programming is a widely used field of optimization for several re=
asons. Many practical problems in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Operations_research" title=3D"Operations research">operations research</a> =
can be expressed as linear programming problems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dantzig=
1982_6-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line=
ar_programming#cite_note-dantzig1982-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Certain special cases of=
 linear programming, such as <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ne=
twork_flow_problem" title=3D"Network flow problem">network flow</a></i> pro=
blems and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-commodity_flow_pro=
blem" title=3D"Multi-commodity flow problem"><i>multicommodity flow</i> pro=
blems</a>, are considered important enough to have much research on special=
ized algorithms. A number of algorithms for other types of optimization pro=
blems work by solving linear programming problems as sub-problems. Historic=
ally, ideas from linear programming have inspired many of the central conce=
pts of optimization theory, such as <i>duality,</i> <i>decomposition,</i> a=
nd the importance of <i>convexity</i> and its generalizations. Likewise, li=
near programming was heavily used in the early formation of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microeconomics" title=3D"Microeconomics">microeco=
nomics</a>, and it is currently utilized in company management, such as pla=
nning, production, transportation, and technology. Although the modern mana=
gement issues are ever-changing, most companies would like to <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Profit_maximization" title=3D"Profit maximizati=
on">maximize profits</a> and minimize costs with limited resources. Google =
also uses linear programming to stabilize YouTube videos.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_p=
rogramming#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Standard_form">Standard for=
m</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
