<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Duality">Duality</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_programming&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Duality"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_linear_program"=
 title=3D"Dual linear program">Dual linear program</a></div>
<p>Every linear programming problem, referred to as a <i>primal</i> problem=
, can be converted into a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_pro=
blem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dual problem">dual problem</a>, which =
provides an upper bound to the optimal value of the primal problem. In matr=
ix form, we can express the <i>primal</i> problem as:
</p>
<dl><dd>Maximize <b>c</b><sup>T</sup><b>x</b>  subject to <i>A</i><b>x</b> =
=E2=89=A4 <b>b</b>, <b>x</b> =E2=89=A5 0;
<dl><dd>with the corresponding <b>symmetric</b> dual problem,</dd></dl></dd=
>
<dd>Minimize  <b>b</b><sup>T</sup><b>y</b>  subject to <i>A</i><sup>T</sup>=
<b>y</b> =E2=89=A5 <b>c</b>, <b>y</b> =E2=89=A5 0.</dd></dl>
<p>An alternative primal formulation is:
</p>
<dl><dd>Maximize <b>c</b><sup>T</sup><b>x</b> subject to <i>A</i><b>x</b> =
=E2=89=A4 <b>b</b>;
<dl><dd>with the corresponding <b>asymmetric</b> dual problem,</dd></dl></d=
d>
<dd>Minimize  <b>b</b><sup>T</sup><b>y</b> subject to <i>A</i><sup>T</sup><=
b>y</b> =3D <b>c</b>, <b>y</b> =E2=89=A5 0.</dd></dl>
<p>There are two ideas fundamental to duality theory. One is the fact that =
(for the symmetric dual) the dual of a dual linear program is the original =
primal linear program. Additionally, every feasible solution for a linear p=
rogram gives a bound on the optimal value of the objective function of its =
dual.  The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weak_duality" title=3D"=
Weak duality">weak duality</a> theorem states that the objective function v=
alue of the dual at any feasible solution is always greater than or equal t=
o the objective function value of the primal at any feasible solution. The =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strong_duality" title=3D"Strong du=
ality">strong duality</a> theorem states that if the primal has an optimal =
solution, <b>x</b><sup>*</sup>, then the dual also has an optimal solution,=
 <b>y</b><sup>*</sup>, and <b>c</b><sup>T</sup><b>x</b><sup>*</sup>=3D<b>b<=
/b><sup>T</sup><b>y</b><sup>*</sup>.
</p><p>A linear program can also be unbounded or infeasible. Duality theory=
 tells us that if the primal is unbounded then the dual is infeasible by th=
e weak duality theorem. Likewise, if the dual is unbounded, then the primal=
 must be infeasible. However, it is possible for both the dual and the prim=
al to be infeasible.  See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_lin=
ear_program" title=3D"Dual linear program">dual linear program</a> for deta=
ils and several more examples.
</p>
