e">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covering_problem" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Covering problem">covering LP</a> is a linear program o=
f the form:
</p>
<dl><dd>Minimize:  <big><b>b</b><sup>T</sup><b>y</b></big>,</dd>
<dd>subject to: <big><i>A</i><sup>T</sup><b>y</b> =E2=89=A5 <b>c</b>, <b>y<=
/b> =E2=89=A5 0</big>,</dd></dl>
<p>such that the matrix <i>A</i> and the vectors <b>b</b> and <b>c</b> are =
non-negative.
</p><p>The dual of a covering LP is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Packing_problem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Packing problem">packin=
g LP</a>, a linear program of the form:
</p>
<dl><dd>Maximize: <big><b>c</b><sup>T</sup><b>x</b></big>,</dd>
<dd>subject to: <big><i>A</i><b>x</b> =E2=89=A4 <b>b</b>, <b>x</b> =E2=89=
=A5 0</big>,</dd></dl>
<p>such that the matrix <i>A</i> and the vectors <b>b</b> and <b>c</b> are =
non-negative.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Examples">Examples</h4><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_programming&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Examples"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Covering and packing LPs commonly arise as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Linear_programming_relaxation" title=3D"Linear programming re=
laxation">linear programming relaxation</a> of a combinatorial problem and =
are important in the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Appr=
oximation_algorithms" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Approximation algorith=
ms">approximation algorithms</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-12"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> For example, the LP relaxations of the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Set_packing" title=3D"Set packing">set packing problem</a=
>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_set_problem" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Independent set problem">independent set probl=
em</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matching_(graph_th=
eory)" title=3D"Matching (graph theory)">matching problem</a> are packing L=
Ps. The LP relaxations of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_=
cover_problem" title=3D"Set cover problem">set cover problem</a>, the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertex_cover_problem" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Vertex cover problem">vertex cover problem</a>, and the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dominating_set_problem" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Dominating set problem">dominating set problem</a> are also=
 covering LPs.
</p><p>Finding a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_colori=
ng" title=3D"Fractional coloring">fractional coloring</a> of a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)" title=3D"Graph (=
discrete mathematics)">graph</a> is another example of a covering LP. In th=
is case, there is one constraint for each vertex of the graph and one varia=
ble for each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_set_(grap=
h_theory)" title=3D"Independent set (graph theory)">independent set</a> of =
the graph.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Complementary_slackness">Co=
mplementary slackness</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DLinear_programming&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"E=
dit section: Complementary slackness"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>It is possible to obtain an optimal solution to the dual when only an op=
timal solution to the primal is known using the complementary slackness the=
orem. The theorem states:
</p><p>Suppose that <b>x</b>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;(<b>x</b><sub>1</sub>,&nbsp;<b>x=
</b><sub>2</sub>,&nbsp;...&nbsp;,&nbsp;<b>x</b><sub><i>n</i></sub>) is prim=
al feasible and that <b>y</b>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;(<b>y</b><sub>1</sub>,&nbsp;<b>=
y</b><sub>2</sub>,&nbsp;...&nbsp;,&nbsp;<b>y</b><sub><i>m</i></sub>) is dua=
l feasible. Let (<b>w</b><sub>1</sub>,&nbsp;<b>w</b><sub>2</sub>,&nbsp;...,=
&nbsp;<b>w</b><sub><i>m</i></sub>) denote the corresponding primal slack va=
riables, and let (<b>z</b><sub>1</sub>,&nbsp;<b>z</b><sub>2</sub>,&nbsp;...=
&nbsp;,&nbsp;<b>z</b><sub><i>n</i></sub>) denote the corresponding dual sla=
ck variables. Then <b>x</b> and <b>y</b> are optimal for their respective p=
roblems if and only if
</p>
<ul><li><b>x</b><sub><i>j</i></sub> <b>z</b><sub><i>j</i></sub>&nbsp;=3D&nb=
sp;0, for <i>j</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2,&nbsp;...&nbsp;,&nbsp;<i>n</i>, =
and</li>
<li><b>w</b><sub><i>i</i></sub> <b>y</b><sub><i>i</i></sub>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;0=
, for <i>i</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2,&nbsp;...&nbsp;,&nbsp;<i>m</i>.</li>=
</ul>
<p>So if the <i>i</i>-th slack variable of the primal is not zero, then the=
 <i>i</i>-th variable of the dual is equal to zero. Likewise, if the <i>j</=
i>-th slack variable of the dual is not zero, then the <i>j</i>-th variable=
 of the primal is equal to zero.
</p><p>This necessary condition for optimality conveys a fairly simple econ=
omic principle.  In standard form (when maximizing), if there is slack in a=
 constrained primal resource (i.e., there are "leftovers"), then additional=
 quantities of that resource must have no value.  Likewise, if there is sla=
ck in the dual (shadow) price non-negativity constraint requirement, i.e., =
the price is not zero, then there must be scarce supplies (no "leftovers").
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Theory">Theory</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_programming&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Theory"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Existence_of_optimal_soluti=
ons">Existence of optimal solutions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_programming&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
13" title=3D"Edit section: Existence of optimal solutions"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Geometrically, the linear constraints define the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Feasible_region" title=3D"Feasible region">feasible regio=
n</a>, which is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polytope"=
 title=3D"Convex polytope">convex polytope</a>. A <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Linear_functional" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear fu=
nctional">linear function</a> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Convex_function" title=3D"Convex function">convex function</a>, which impl=
ies that every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_minimum" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Local minimum">local minimum</a> is a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_minimum" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Global minimum">global minimum</a>; similarly, a linear function is a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concave_function" title=3D"Concave =
function">concave function</a>, which implies that every <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_maximum" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Local =
maximum">local maximum</a> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gl=
obal_maximum" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Global maximum">global maximum=
</a>.
</p><p>An optimal solution need not exist, for two reasons. First, if the c=
onstraints are inconsistent, then no feasible solution exists: For instance=
, the constraints <b>x</b>&nbsp;=E2=89=A5&nbsp;2 and <b>x</b>&nbsp;=E2=89=
=A4&nbsp;1 cannot be satisfied jointly; in this case, we say that the LP is=
 <i>infeasible</i>. Second, when the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Polytope" title=3D"Polytope">polytope</a> is unbounded in the direction =
of the gradient of the objective function (where the gradient of the object=
ive function is the vector of the coefficients of the objective function), =
then no optimal value is attained because it is always possible to do bette=
r than any finite value of the objective function.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Optimal_vertices_(and_rays)=
_of_polyhedra"><span id=3D"Optimal_vertices_.28and_rays.29_of_polyhedra"></=
span>Optimal vertices (and rays) of polyhedra</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_programming&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;=
section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Optimal vertices (and rays) of polyhed=
ra"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>Otherwise, if a feasible solution exists and if the constraint set is bo=
unded, then the optimum value is always attained on the boundary of the con=
straint set, by the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_pri=
nciple" title=3D"Maximum principle">maximum principle</a></i> for <i><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_function" title=3D"Convex functio=
n">convex functions</a></i> (alternatively, by the <i>minimum</i> principle=
 for <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concave_function" title=3D=
"Concave function">concave functions</a></i>) since linear functions are bo=
th convex and concave. However, some problems have distinct optimal solutio=
ns; for example, the problem of finding a feasible solution to a system of =
linear inequalities is a linear programming problem in which the objective =
function is the zero function (i.e., the constant function taking the value=
 zero everywhere). For this feasibility problem with the zero-function for =
its objective-function, if there are two distinct solutions, then every con=
vex combination of the solutions is a solution.
</p><p>The vertices of the polytope are also called <i>basic feasible solut=
ions</i>. The reason for this choice of name is as follows. Let <i>d</i> de=
note the number of variables. Then the fundamental theorem of linear inequa=
lities implies (for feasible problems) that for every vertex <b>x</b><sup>*=
</sup> of the LP feasible region, there exists a set of <i>d</i> (or fewer)=
 inequality constraints from the LP such that, when we treat those <i>d</i>=
 constraints as equalities, the unique solution is <b>x</b><sup>*</sup>. Th=
ereby we can study these vertices by means of looking at certain subsets of=
 the set of all constraints (a discrete set), rather than the continuum of =
LP solutions. This principle underlies the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Simplex_algorithm" title=3D"Simplex algorithm">simplex algorithm</=
a> for solving linear programs.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Algorithms">Algorithms</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_programmi=
ng&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Algorithms"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_numerical_analys=
is_topics#Linear_programming" title=3D"List of numerical analysis topics">L=
ist of numerical analysis topics =C2=A7&nbsp;Linear programming</a></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Frame"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Linear_Programming_Feasible_Region.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><=
img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Linear=
_Programming_Feasible_Region.svg/250px-Linear_Programming_Feasible_Region.s=
vg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-el=
ement" data-file-width=3D"250" data-file-height=3D"250"></a><figcaption>In =
a linear programming problem, a series of linear constraints produces a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_set" title=3D"Convex set">conv=
ex</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feasible_region" title=3D"F=
easible region">feasible region</a> of possible values for those variables.=
 In the two-variable case this region is in the shape of a convex <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_polygon" title=3D"Simple polygon">=
simple polygon</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Basis_exchange_algorithms">=
Basis exchange algorithms</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DLinear_programming&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=
=3D"Edit section: Basis exchange algorithms"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Simplex_algorithm_of_Dantzi=
g">Simplex algorithm of Dantzig</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DLinear_programming&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" =
title=3D"Edit section: Simplex algorithm of Dantzig"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simplex_algorithm" title=3D=
"Simplex algorithm">simplex algorithm</a>, developed by <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Dantzig" title=3D"George Dantzig">George Dantz=
ig</a> in 1947, solves LP problems by constructing a feasible solution at a=
 vertex of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polytope" title=3D"=
Polytope">polytope</a> and then walking along a path on the edges of the po=
lytope to vertices with non-decreasing values of the objective function unt=
il an optimum is reached for sure. In many practical problems, "<a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simplex_algorithm#Degeneracy:_stalling_and_cy=
cling" title=3D"Simplex algorithm">stalling</a>" occurs: many pivots are ma=
de with no increase in the objective function.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DT03_13-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_progr=
amming#cite_note-DT03-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Padberg_14-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming=
#cite_note-Padberg-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In rare practical problems, the usual =
versions of the simplex algorithm may actually "cycle".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Padberg_14-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Linear_programming#cite_note-Padberg-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> To avoid cycles, resea=
rchers developed new pivoting rules.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FukudaTerlaky_15-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_progra=
mming#cite_note-FukudaTerlaky-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In practice, the simplex <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al=
gorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a> is quite efficient and can be gu=
aranteed to find the global optimum if certain precautions against <i>cycli=
ng</i> are taken. The simplex algorithm has been proved to solve "random" p=
roblems efficiently, i.e. in a cubic number of steps,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_progr=
amming#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which is similar to its behavior on practi=
cal problems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DT03_13-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-DT03-13"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Todd_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-Todd-17"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>However, the simplex algorithm has poor worst-case behavior: Klee an=
d Minty constructed a family of linear programming problems for which the s=
implex method takes a number of steps exponential in the problem size.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-DT03_13-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-DT03-13"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Murty_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Linear_programming#cite_note-Murty-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-P=
S_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear=
_programming#cite_note-PS-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In fact, for some time it was not=
 known whether the linear programming problem was solvable in <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_time" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Polynomial time">polynomial time</a>, i.e. of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/P_(complexity)" title=3D"P (complexity)">complexity class P</a=
>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Criss-cross_algorithm">Cris=
s-cross algorithm</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DLinear_programming&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit =
section: Criss-cross algorithm"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Like the simplex algorithm of Dantzig, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Criss-cross_algorithm" title=3D"Criss-cross algorithm">criss-cr=
oss algorithm</a> is a basis-exchange algorithm that pivots between bases. =
However, the criss-cross algorithm need not maintain feasibility, but can p=
ivot rather from a feasible basis to an infeasible basis. The criss-cross a=
lgorithm does not have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_comple=
xity" title=3D"Time complexity">polynomial time-complexity</a> for linear p=
rogramming. Both algorithms visit all&nbsp;2<sup><i>D</i></sup> corners of =
a (perturbed) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_cube" title=3D"=
Unit cube">cube</a> in dimension&nbsp;<i>D</i>, the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Klee%E2%80%93Minty_cube" title=3D"Klee=E2=80=93Minty cube=
">Klee=E2=80=93Minty cube</a>, in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Worst-case_complexity" title=3D"Worst-case complexity">worst case</a>.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-FukudaTerlaky_15-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-FukudaTerlaky-15"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Roos_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#cite_note-Roos-20"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Interior_point">Interior po=
int</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_p=
rogramming&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Inter=
ior point"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>In contrast to the simplex algorithm, which finds an optimal solution by=
 traversing the edges between vertices on a polyhedral set, interior-point =
methods move through the interior of the feasible region.
</p>
